Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The team of Europe has won the Ryder Cup in 2018 by defeating the team of the United States with a final score of 16.5 against 10.5 points on the Le Golf National field outside Paris, France.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained its throne when the team, led by Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, reached the 14.5 points it needed to conquer the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who struggled most of the competition, made his initial stroke in the water on the 16th hole, which is a par 3, and lost his game against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone brightly in all his games and became 1 of 4 players to get the result 5-0-0, since the race started using its current format in 1979.
Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark, who was at the bottom of the ranking of the European team.
Dustin Johnson, who is at the top of the list of the best golfers in the world, lost 2 and 1 against Ian Poulter from England who may have played in his last race for the Ryder Cup.
Spaniard Sergio Garcia, who has played eight times for the Ryder Cup, became the most successful European player in the competition with 25.5 career points.
