Latest news of algae blooms: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest news from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of algae blossoms in parts of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the FWC, abrasion of algae is reported in certain areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting decreasing concentrations.
The algal flower covers an approximately 200-kilometer coastal line from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee counties.
You can find unique flowers about 16 miles from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algae flowers have also been reported in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or around Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations beyond Hillsborough County, very low to high concentrations in Manatee County, very low to high concentrations in or around Sarasota County, very low to moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, very low to high concentrations in or around Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
